<span id="freeTextContainer17742693302475507325">I&apos;ve been reading the last few chapters with a Queen&apos;s song &quot;Bohemian Rhapsody&quot; and now I think that line &quot;So you think you can love me and leave me to die&quot; is a perfect quote as description to this amazing book. <br/><br/>I had no idea about this book and its author when I decided to read it. And now I&apos;m genuinely surprised with the plot and ethic aesthetics which author has not only mentioned, but naturally written in the lives of characters.<br/><br/>The last part of the book reminded me of the book &quot;One Hundred</span>
  <span id="freeText17742693302475507325" style="display:none">I've been reading the last few chapters with a Queen's song "Bohemian Rhapsody" and now I think that line "So you think you can love me and leave me to die" is a perfect quote as description to this amazing book. <br /><br />I had no idea about this book and its author when I decided to read it. And now I'm genuinely surprised with the plot and ethic aesthetics which author has not only mentioned, but naturally written in the lives of characters.<br /><br />The last part of the book reminded me of the book "One Hundred Years of Solitude" by Gabriel García Márquez. Ghost, natural phenomena which express emotions and feelings, clairvoyants and gods. And only after finishing, I have found out that "Dona Flor..." was written in a genre of Magical Realism (along with "One Hundred Years...".<br /><br />I really recommend this book. It can make you smile and think. <br /><br /></span>
