    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_861545617" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/861545617" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3143117-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1571421692p2/3143117.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/861545617?book_show_action=true">Feb 21, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/3143117-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780307279552" href="/book/show/2278185.Do_a_Flor_y_sus_dos_maridos">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=latin-american-lit">latin-american-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=espa%C3%B1ol">español</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=portuguese-lit">portuguese-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=brazilian">brazilian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer861545617" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3176704574085117415">&quot;Yo soy el Maestro del Absurdo&quot; says one of the priests putting the spell on Vadinho, Dona Flor&apos;s first husband, to return him back to the land of the dead. The Master of the Absurd could be said about Jorge Amado as well. This book is very funny and even absurd at times but more importantly, well worth the read.<br/><br/>I vaguely remember liking the movie, made in 1976 with Sonia Braga (or maybe I just remember Sonia Braga?) but this book was a complete enjoyable read. From the start when her gambling, </span>
  <span id="freeText3176704574085117415" style="display:none">"Yo soy el Maestro del Absurdo" says one of the priests putting the spell on Vadinho, Dona Flor's first husband, to return him back to the land of the dead. The Master of the Absurd could be said about Jorge Amado as well. This book is very funny and even absurd at times but more importantly, well worth the read.<br /><br />I vaguely remember liking the movie, made in 1976 with Sonia Braga (or maybe I just remember Sonia Braga?) but this book was a complete enjoyable read. From the start when her gambling, womanizing husband Vadinho drops dead I laughed (trust me - it is very funny) and then, the book took a more serious turn when she married the very staid pharmacist husband Dr. Teodoro and I enjoyed Amado's reflections on life and marriage. Then, when Doña Flor celebrates her first year marriage to Teodoro, in walks a very naked Vadinho, coming back to get into bed with Doña Flor one more time (who loves you, baby?). The ending becomes absurd (check out the Martians) and the tale is done.<br /><br />The characters are just so... absorbing. Doña Flor's mom is a real shark. When Doña Flor and Vadinho get married, she leaves her daughter because she married a "low-life" and when Vadinho dies, good old mom returns to say "I told you so" (in much more colourful language). Yep, a real witch. Vadinho, even as a ghost, can't keep his hands off Doña Flor's students and even scares one of his gambling buddies even to stop his gambling obsession. Teodoro is rather dull but loves his wife as best as he can but he loves playing his bassoon in the orchestra even more. Doña Flor wants to succeed as the owner of her Cooking School and wants to be a good wife. Written in 1966, there is a mix of feminism, class and old fashioned views mixed into one person. She is definitely not one dimensional. After Vadinho dies, Doña Flor begins having erotic dreams that at first are funny, but then Amado shows us how tormented she is becoming. Enter Teodoro to cure that (or not). <br /><br />The movie cuts to the chase; the book brings it out so much more. It surprised me that as much as it is funny and absurd, it is moving and reflective. Amado doesn't really explain everything - leaving the magic realism to do its work unfolding as it does (I like this). If you are interested in Latin American literature, this book is not to be missed. Although it took me so long to read, blame it on the movie. However I did read the book in Spanish (sorry not the original Portuguese but close enough).<br /><br />One minor complaint, this book was published in 9 pt font which really was a tad small.<br /><br />Doña Flor</span>
  <a data-text-id="3176704574085117415" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


