<div id="review_2524477979" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2524477979" />
    <a title="Leila" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/86535390-leila"><img alt="Leila" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607211288p2/86535390.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2524477979?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leila" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leila" href="/user/show/86535390-leila">Leila</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2524477979&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2524477979" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16006346125530001889">Interesting and colourful narrative of a young woman&apos;s struggle to come to terms with her sexuality in the midst of a very conservative, religious (and hypocritical) Bahian society.<br/>In my view, the book is made of three parts: first part is husband Vadinho, which represents Eros love but also a life of poverty, neglect and betrayal; the second part relates to husband Teodoro, which stands for cast love and integrity, but also monotony and boredom; and finally the third part - Dona Flor&apos;s inner st</span>
  <span id="freeText16006346125530001889" style="display:none">Interesting and colourful narrative of a young woman's struggle to come to terms with her sexuality in the midst of a very conservative, religious (and hypocritical) Bahian society.<br />In my view, the book is made of three parts: first part is husband Vadinho, which represents Eros love but also a life of poverty, neglect and betrayal; the second part relates to husband Teodoro, which stands for cast love and integrity, but also monotony and boredom; and finally the third part - Dona Flor's inner struggle to live with both husbands, symbolising her battle to overcome a repressed sexuality and free herself from society's stigma of women's sexual desire.<br />The last few chapters contain a very colourful battle of the heaven gods for Vadinho's soul, which represents Flor's internal conflict (and triumph) over her shame in longing for a kind of sex that was deemed dirty and unbecoming of a good and respecting wife.<br />Instead of public disgrace and moral regret, allowing herself to fantasise, masturbate and encourage her new husband Teodoro to innovate in their sexual routine (all because of her metaphorical giving-in to Vadinho's ghostly sexual advances) actually resulted in a much happier and fulfilled Dona Flor.<br />It took me a while to get to this conclusion but, in my opinion, the real message of the book is to be true to ourselves, and realise that often the voice in our heads holding us back from happiness is nothing more than our own projection of how we think society would judge us for our fantasies. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16006346125530001889" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

